The key insight in this problem is to recognize that the medians intersect at the centroid, which divides each median into segments with a 2:1 ratio. By using this property, we can find the lengths of the segments formed by the centroid. Since the medians are perpendicular, we can form a right-angled triangle and apply the Pythagorean theorem to find the required side length.
{{DGM:268eb9dd96cb1f72}}

Point $G$ is the centroid of $\triangle DEF$, so $DG:GP = EG:GQ = 2:1$.  Therefore, $DG = \frac23(DP) = 12$ and $EG = \frac23(EQ) =16$, so applying the Pythagorean Theorem to $\triangle EGD$ gives us $DE = \sqrt{EG^2 + GD^2} = \boxed{20}$.

The solution uses polynomial long division to find the remainder when $x^3$ is divided by $x^2 + 5x + 1$. The divisor is written on the left side of the division bracket, and the dividend is written inside the bracket. The division is performed by subtracting multiples of the divisor from the dividend until the degree of the remainder is less than the degree of the divisor.
1. Set up the polynomial long division:
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cc cc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{x} & -5 \\
   \cline{2-5}
   x^2 + 5x + 1 & x^3& & &  \\
   \end{array}
   $$

2. Divide $x^3$ by $x^2$ to get $x$. Multiply the divisor by $x$ and subtract from the dividend:
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cc cc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{x} & -5 \\
   \cline{2-5}
   x^2 + 5x + 1 & x^3& & &  \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{x^3} & +5x^2 & +x  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -5x^2 & -x & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

3. Bring down the next term of the dividend ($0$) and repeat the division process. Multiply the divisor by $-5$ and subtract from the current dividend:
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cc cc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{x} & -5 \\
   \cline{2-5}
   x^2 + 5x + 1 & x^3& & &  \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{x^3} & +5x^2 & +x  \\
   \cline{2-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -5x^2 & -x & \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -5x^2 & -25x & -5 \\
   \cline{3-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 24x & +5 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

4. The remainder has a degree less than the divisor, so the division is complete. The remainder is $24x + 5$.
The remainder when $x^3$ is divided by $x^2 + 5x + 1$ is $\boxed{24x + 5}$.
